About the data¶

For this problem set, we will apply unsupervised and supervised learning skills to develop a diagnostic model for hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) from transcriptomics data. This dataset came from Gene Expression Omnibus GSE14520

We will also try to identify a small set of genes that are important for the diagnosis. This will let us develop a low-cost PCR or Nanostring assay (rather than performing microarray or RNA-seq on every new patient)

In [129]:
probe_to_gene = {}

for probe_id in annot.index:
    if not pd.isna(annot.loc[probe_id, 'Gene Symbol']): ## ignore rows with missing gene symbol
        gene_symbol = annot.loc[probe_id, 'Gene Symbol'].split()[0] ## add .split()[0] because some rows contain multiple gene symbols
        probe_to_gene[probe_id] = gene_symbol
  1. Apply the mapping to the column names
In [157]:

Q7: Identify genes that are differentially expressed¶

This microarray dataset has been normalized and log-transformed. Hence, t-tests can be used

We are collecting the statistical test results in a new DataFrame with p-value and log FC

In [290]:
ttest_results = pd.DataFrame(0, index = selected_exp_data.columns, columns = ['P-value', 'HCC/Normal Log FC'])

for gene in selected_exp_data.columns:
    normal_exp = selected_exp_data[gene].loc[cancer_labels == 'normal']
    cancer_exp = selected_exp_data[gene].loc[cancer_labels == 'HCC']
    
    ttest_results.loc[gene, 'P-value'] = ttest_ind(normal_exp, cancer_exp, equal_var = False, alternative = 'two-sided')[1]
    
    antilog_cancer_exp = cancer_exp**10 # Covert log-transformed values into original values before log2FC calculation
    antilog_normal_exp = normal_exp**10
    
    ttest_results.loc[gene, 'HCC/Normal Log FC'] = np.log2(antilog_cancer_exp.mean()/antilog_normal_exp.mean()) 
    
ttest_results.head()

Q11: Examine the coefficients to understand how the model works¶

Draw two scatter plots: one with HCC/Normal Log FC vs Coefficient and another with -Log10 P-value vs Coefficient

Does the model consistently assign large magnitude of coefficients (either positive or negative) to genes with high FCs or low p-values?

Ans: Yes but only in the relationship between coefficient and log2FC. For example, there is a negative relationship between coefficient and log2FC, with more negative coefficient leading to more positive log2FC and vice versa. The trend is unclear in the relationship between coefficient and negative log p-value although the larger negative and positive coefficient are related to high minus log p-values.

Can you explain why the model may behave the way it is?

Ans: Because log2FC has both negative and positive values, the model can classify the patient types according to the strong relationship between coefficient and log2FC. The p-values have only postive values, thus, the trend is not clear. Nevertheless, the model can capture some degree of larger minus log p-value (more significant p-value) in both negative and positive log2FC genes. Therefore, the scatter plot of minus Log P-value vs coefficient has biphasic appearance.

RFECV (Recursive Feature Elimination with Cross-Validation) iteratively remove gene(s) with the lowest impact on the model and measure the model performance
